    "summary": "Mini-retro: proactive guidance worked, approval loop was wasteful",
    "content": "Lea's mini-retro observations for Step 8:\n\n**What went well:**\n- Proactive CSS guidance sent before implementation started -- this meant the Driver had token references, class names, and HTML structure suggestions ready from the beginning. The final CSS was consistent with the design system as a result.\n- The pill-badge and `<time>` element catches were genuine quality improvements. The review process worked as intended.\n- Two-field add form was a new pattern handled well. The vertical stacked layout was actually a better choice than my initial single-row suggestion -- it gave each field its own visible label.\n\n**What could improve:**\n- My approval was sent but not registered by the Driver, leading to 5+ repeated confirmations. This wasted everyone's time. The root cause appears to be context compaction dropping earlier messages. **Suggestion**: When giving consensus approval, the reviewer should also tag the coordinator or use a standardized phrase that's easy to search for in message history (e.g., \"CONSENSUS: APPROVED\" as the first line).\n- The staging gap (fixes on disk but not staged) created unnecessary confusion during re-review. **Suggestion**: After applying fixes, always run `git add` before requesting re-review so the staged state matches what reviewers see on disk.\n\n**No process changes proposed** -- just awareness items. The pipeline worked correctly overall."
  }
}
